# Swift Standards

Target Swift 6.2 where possible. Fall back gracefully to 5.9+ when deployment constraints require it. Enforce with SwiftLint.

## Architecture
- MVVM with SwiftUI: View observes ViewModel, ViewModel owns business logic.
- Prefer value types (`struct`, `enum`) over reference types.
- Protocol composition over class inheritance.
- Dependency injection through initializer or `@Environment`.
- Split files at approximately 300 lines.

## Concurrency (General)
- `async`/`await` for all asynchronous work. No `DispatchQueue` in new code.
- `@MainActor` for UI-bound code. Actors for shared mutable state.
- `Sendable` compliance throughout. Handle `Task.checkCancellation()`.
- `TaskGroup` for structured parallel work.

## Concurrency (Swift 6.0+)
- Complete concurrency checking is enabled by default. Fix warnings, do not suppress them.
- Region-based isolation (SE-0414) allows the compiler to prove safety without manual `Sendable` conformance in many cases. Trust it.
- Use the `sending` keyword to transfer values between isolation regions when needed.

## Concurrency (Swift 6.2)
- Use `-default-isolation MainActor` for UI-focused modules. This makes all types and functions main-actor-isolated by default, eliminating boilerplate `@MainActor` annotations.
- Mark functions that must run off the main actor with `@concurrent` (SE-0461).
- `Task.immediate` starts execution synchronously on the caller's executor. Use for work that must begin before the next suspension point.
- Named tasks: pass `name:` to `Task.init()`, `Task.detached()`, and `addTask()` for debuggability.
- `weak let` (SE-0481) for immutable weak references. Enables `Sendable` conformance on classes with weak references.
- `isolated deinit` for actor-isolated classes that need to access their own state during cleanup.
- Global-actor isolated conformances: `@MainActor Equatable` restricts conformance to the main actor.

## SwiftUI
- Small, focused view structs. Extract `ViewModifier` for reuse.
- `@Observable` macro (iOS 17+) for modern observation.
- `Observations` struct (Swift 6.2) for programmatic observation of `@Observable` changes outside SwiftUI.
- `NavigationStack` with programmatic navigation paths.
- Accessibility: labels, traits, and VoiceOver support on every interactive element. This is not optional.
- Dark mode and Dynamic Type support required on all screens.

## New Types (Swift 6.2)
- `InlineArray<N, Element>` for fixed-size, stack-allocated arrays. Use when the count is known at compile time and heap allocation is undesirable.
- `Span` for safe alternatives to `UnsafeBufferPointer`.
- Raw identifiers (backtick syntax) for test names: `func \`user login succeeds with valid token\`()` instead of a separate `@Test("...")` description string.
- Default values in string interpolation: `"\(age, default: "Unknown")"` for optionals with cross-type defaults.

## Safety
- No force unwraps (`!`) except in tests with a comment explaining the invariant.
- `[weak self]` in closures that outlive their owner.
- `Codable` with explicit `CodingKeys` when API shapes differ from the model.
- Keychain for secrets. Never hardcode API keys.
- Opt-in strict memory safety (SE-0458): use `@safe`/`@unsafe` annotations and the `unsafe` keyword when interfacing with unsafe APIs.

## Documentation
- Public types and methods require a doc comment describing behavior and contracts.
- One-liner doc comments for simple functions: `/// Clamp value to [lo, hi].`
- Do not restate parameter types in prose. Describe what the function does, not its signature.

## Testing
- XCTest with async test methods (or Swift Testing with `@Test`).
- Swift 6.2: use raw identifiers for human-readable test names without duplication.
- Mock via protocols, not concrete classes. Inject dependencies.
- Snapshot testing for view regression on key screens.
- Test naming: `test_<behavior>_when_<condition>_expects_<result>` (XCTest) or backtick names (Swift Testing).
- Minimum 80% coverage on business logic. Do not write tests for trivial getters.
